        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> <BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=2 face="Verdana" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>HP does NOT equal more mana. Let me say it again: Lich and max HP have NOTHING to do with each other. You know why? Have you ever heard of Vexing? Yep, it's true! Vexing and BoD regen HP! So all you idiots who say that HP helps with Lich are just that, idiots.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana" size=2 id=quote>Ok you blithering little angry lost child...I'll explain this in small words so you can understand.</P><P>What was correctly said above, and misquoted by you, is that HP = mana...not "more" mana.  No one implied that having high max hps meant you had more mana.  Simply that the more hps you have, the more you can convert to mana.</P><P>Now any daft fool knows our lifetap DoTs are, well, less than efficient.  They cost quite a chunk of mana.  The more max hps you have, the more wiggle room you have before you need to tap those hps back.  The longer you stay Liched without tapping, the more efficiently you regen mana, and yes, before you start screaming it here, hp regen does markedly increase efficiency.  Moreso than raw hps.</P><P>Granted, for the sake of efficieny, adding on more hps after about 1800 or so doesn't help much...but only in terms of efficieny.</P><P>However, after a certain point...and it's going to be different for each individual, depending on how they play...the size of your total mana pool is also irrelevant.  All that matters is how fast you regain mana.  Total mana pool is only meaningful for situations where you have to use a lot of mana in a short period of time...like breaking a camp, or dealing with adds.  For almost all other situations xping or raiding, it's more important to be able to regain mana at a rate somewhat near the rate you are using it...that's what keeps you and/or your group going for the long run.  So adding more mana items really doesn't add much.</P><P>Adding more hps however, always helps.  You may not get any more efficient after you pass a certain threshold, but you become a hell of a lot more survivable.  Plain and simple.  You can survive running out of mana, running out of hps however...</P><P>If you still don't undstand the advantage of having more hps, then I suggest you go (back to?) play a druid, because you clearly don't understand the balancing act that it is to be an efficient, effective necro.</P><P></P><P>--Nergal Teir'Draconis, Knights of Twilight (Tunare)</font></td>
