        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Juryiel</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Angrier the point they're trying to make about HP being more mana is as follows.</P><P>Case 1:  1000hps.  Lets say for safety reasons of the average non suicidal necro, the necro in this case is willing to lich down to 30% hp maximum.  That's 700 HP missing off the necro.  He casts vexing and heals those 700 hp for 495 mana.  This takes about 5.7 ticks of vexing.  The spell is nine ticks and 122hps per tick (i used Castersrealm info so not sure if its right) so every tick after that the necro is only gaining 53 hps per tick (because arch lich is taking 53 hps down every tick) instead of 122 per tick for 3.3 ticks.  That's a total 227.7 hps.  So although vexing heals for 1098 / 495 mana you only healed for 870.3 for the same ammount of mana.  I'm sure you can see the difference in those numbers.  Basically, the HP healed / Mana used ratio becomes worse, so you lose more mana due to not having enough Hps.  A necro with about 1.6k hp gets rid of this problem.  The argument that lifetaps are not affected by how much HP you have is therefore wrong when you consider lifetap dots.  </P><P>Case 2: This relates to just a lack of better stat.  Once your mana drops bellow full, as long as you have enough mana to cast all the spells that the fight will require, mana regen comes into play rather than raw mana.  Assume you have a manapool of 3000.  If the maximum mana to have been used at any given time in the fight is , say, 30% (im not usually under 70% so that's a good number), that means that only 900 raw mana will be gone at any given time in the fight.  The rest of your mana pool will depend solely on your mana regen.  So a necro with 3000 mana will be able to solo the same stuff as a necro with 900 mana assuming they both use the same spells.  Now assume at the end of the fight the necro with 3000 manapool is left at about 90% mana due to all the regens.  He's only missing 300 mana.  The necro with 900 mana pool is also left with the same raw mana missing, so he's left with 600 mana and at about 66.7% mana.  Here the necro with 3000 mana can keep fighting but the necro with 900 mana has to rest after every fight recovering 300 mana per fight.  If the necro in case A keeps going he will be at 900 mana after 7 fights.  So after the 8th fight the necro with 3000 mana pool and the necro with 900 mana pool will be at the same place.  Sure the necro in the first senario will have gotten 8 more kills but that's it.  Even if the necro with 3000 mana meds to full, it will take him the time that the necro with 900 mana kills 8 mobs, so it will even it out.  I'm not sure if this is confusing but im fairly certain that a) The math works or b) its 2:30 am and im too tired to think logically.  Also consider that the mana of 3000 to 900 is quite absurd, no one at 60 will have 900 mana, so the difference will be a lot less, maybe even less than 1 fight.  So although HP after 1.6k-2000 becomes less useful in soloing situations, it DOES provide survivability whereas mana (a realistic comparison, not the one I presented here) provides very little advantage.  </P><P>Case 3:  Heals.  The more HP you have the more HPs you can heal in a quicker time (though overall it won't be much difference since you have to drain the HPs you give.)  But since time is a factor in healing others HP helps here.  This works both for your pet when soloing and for groups.  I think this is fairly clear but if you don't see it i can give you an example just let me know.  </P><P>With all that said, is HP more important than every other effect / stat?  Probably not, again, as many people have said, its balance.  But most necros who do preach HP > all are necros who are either raid necros or who wish to become raid necros.  And when you consider raids HP usefulness goes up quite a bit.</P><P>Juryiel Shadowangel<BR>56 Defiler</font></td>
