        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Drexyll</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> I hate to say it, but some of you folks really missed the boat on this one, and the fact that Angrier didn't call you on this really just proves he's really trying to make a valid argument and not sink to the depths of a flame-fest like some of you.  I love the argument/flame that "well you just don't take as many risks as we do, so that's why we need HP more than you do".  You folks DO realize that Angrier (like yours untruly) plays on a PVP server, right?  He's in more danger going to his hometown to buy a stack of muffins than you "holier-than-thou" folks are in your uber-leet xp spots.  You have to worry about the occasional bad-pull dealing more dmg than you expected.  We have to worry about 2 wizards and an epic mage pet trying to eat us for breakfast at any given moment.  I'm willing to bet that in an average week of playing, red players take considerably more damage than most blue players do.  Plus, we're in danger ALL the time, not just when we choose to be.  See the fundamental flaw of that particular flame (thinly veiled as an argument) yet?</P><P>Some of you made some valid points, and kudos to you for being adults about it.  When someone presents an opposing viewpoint, one does a serious disservice to his or her self when they act like a child and start hurling insults and names instead of simply arguing their point.  I was pretty shocked to see people I highly respect behave in such a manner in this thread.  Sad indeed.</P><P>Now, on to my opinion on HP's.  There needs to be a "balance" IMO, of HPs and initial mana (int/mana gear).  I personally (as well as Angrier) also need to take resist gear into consideration due to our environment (another point a lot of ppl missed before replying).  I personally didn't start working on HP gear until around lvl 50 or so, and I was able to fight/pull nonstop before I had any.  Like Angrier said, when I got low on HP, I cast BoD, or whatever lifetap DOT I had.  Folks can scream till they'r blue in the face about how inefficient lifetap DOTs are, but my rule of thumb has always been that I should end each fight with a single mob at (or damn close to) FM, and ya know what? I always did, even before upping my HP's to the point that I needed BoD less.</P><P>Actually having some added HP's has certainly helped a great deal, both in survivability (especially from unexpected PVP assaults) and <BR>in increasing the amount of time I could lich without needing a heal.  It certainly is one of our most important stats.  HOWEVER, some people take that to the extreme and severely gimp their initial mana pool in favor of hitpoints.  While I can see situations where that would be beneficial (being the main puller on a large-mob raid, for example), as a "permanent stat", it just doesnt work for me.  I had to BALANCE the two.  The KEY point some people are missing is that it all depends upon your INDIVIDUAL playstyle.  I had at one time went "overboard" with hitpoints (due in no small part to recommendations from people here).  The result?  MY PERSONAL playstyle often involves engaging numerous mobs at once.  It's fun.  What happened when I had shit-tons of HP and considerably less mana was that when I had 5 Dar Ghoul Knights on Jabober and myself, I found myself running dangerously low on mana while I worked to keep everything under control and keep the pet and I alive.  It didn't matter that I could lich back a lot of mana.  That takes TIME.  Time is something you don't have in a situation like that.  Did the added HPs allow me to take more hits?  Sure, but the added mana would have negated the NEED to take as many hits, as I could have polished the enemies off sooner.  The answer?  BALANCE the added HP's (which, as stated, DO help) with a large enough initial mana pool.  It's really quite simple.  But again, that's MY playstyle.  As stated in another thread, one of the "cool" things about our class is that no two necros have the same playstyle.  What works for one might not work for another.  To rant and rave that your way is right, and anyone that disagrees is a moron, is at best childish, and honestly rather uninformed.  There is no "right" answer to a question like this.  To get your proverbial panties in a wad because someone doesn't play the same way YOU do is laughable.</P><P></P><P><BR><img src="http://www.onethirtyeight.com/graphics-2/cg.gif"></font></td>
