        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Savan</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Certainly some valid issues with the HP argument (and this shouldn't be news to anyone here -- we've seen this argument 100 times before), but the real answer is balance as you truely need a balance of all three factors (FT, Regen and HP).  Mana pool isn't really even part of the discussion nor should ANY necromancer focus effort on increasing your mana pool with the exception of some lower levels.</P><P>With that said, the one simple problem with this "anti-HP" position is that HP will ultimately prove FAR more important simply because Regen and FT have hard caps at which point you receive no additional benefit.  Not to mention the effective "soft cap" on regen where once you are able to cancel the effects of Lich (or come close) you are seeing massively diminished returns.  HP has no such cap and I guarantee you are going to want every scrap of HP you can dig up come PoP.</P><P>Those are the realities based purely on numbers, but there's also a massive "X-Factor" associated with having more HP.  A few people have touched on this factor and it primarily has to do with greatly enhanced flexibility in all aspects of the game -- raid, group and solo -- not to mention things like exploration, twinking, etc.  There is no question in my mind that I would be able to do all of these things better than a comparably equipped Angrier but who happened to have 1000 or more fewer hp than I did.  I would be able to solo in spots he would not thus earning faster and better experience with better efficiency, group more effectively and do more things in those groups, provide better heal to mana ratios for clerics, shaman and druids thus increasing their efficiency and of course survive the obligatory AOEs and nukes far better in raid situations.</P><P>That's really just the tip of the iceberg though.  There are FAR more subtleties associated with a large HP pool than I've mentioned here.  It's pretty silly to argue otherwise.</P><P><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14661" target="_blank">Savan</a><BR><a href="http://www.afterlifeguild.org/" target="_blank">Afterlife</a></P><P>Edited by - Savan on 09/30/2002  16:29:21</P><P>Edited by - Savan on 09/30/2002  16:40:43</font></td>
